            <div class="gen-group">
              
              <div class="gen-group__content">
                <p class="subheading">Site managed by</p>
                <h2>Cymric Limited</h2>
              </div>
            </div>
        
        <div class="gen-content">
          <p>The Lower Weir site at Bromfield became operational on 8th November 2012. This section of the river Teme in the South Shropshire countryside, has a larger feeding capacity than its smaller sister site located upstream.</p>
<p>Located on the Earl of Plymouth’s Estate, the site was initially conceived with a private wire to feed electricity to Oakly Park, with 80% of output being transferred to the Local Distribution Network. The arrival of Piclo provides greater scope for Cymric to manage the supply of renewable energy to the local region, whilst offering significant cost savings.</p>
<p>Cymric’s long term vision has led to a considerable investment in renewable energy in this site, and sister sites: <a href="http://piclo.uk/p/cymric-upper-weir/zv9UB">Cymric Upper Weir</a> and <a href="https://piclo.uk/p/bromfield-sand-gravel-solar/J3wU8">Bromfield Sand &amp; Gravel Solar</a>. By offsetting carbon dioxide emissions and providing significant clean energy, through hydro and solar power, Cymric is working towards delivering a more sustainable future for the Estate, its farms and businesses, which include Ludlow Food Centre and Bromfield Sand &amp; Gravel. Sustainable continuity is the driving force of the business - supporting the local community and its rural way of life for generations to come.</p>
          <p class="read-more"><a href="#" class="button">Read More</a></p>
        </div>
        

